EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small tornado touched down but did no damage.

A tornado touched down near Greenbriar Drive and moved west  northwest.  A Chickee Hut at the Ann Marie Motel was damaged as were a fence and a portion of the motel roof.  Power lines were blown down onto I-95 and trees were uprooted and street signs blown down along the path.
An F0 tornado touched down briefly in a rural area west of Ft. Pierce. The tornado damaged a mobile home, overturned a farm tractor and blew down about 25 citrus trees.
A small tornado touched down but did no damage.
A small tornado touched down but did no damage.
A waterspout came ashore and overturned a vehicle on Lighthouse Road in Carrabelle.  Reported by the Franklin County EMA.

A waterspout moved onshore and caused minor damage at the U.S. Navy Station just south of Pascagoula.  The weak tornado damaged several cars, a recreational vehicle, a power pole, and the roof of the fire station. Eyewitness said the tornado/waterspout traveled north up the Pascagoula River for a short distance then dissipated.

A funnel cloud persisted over southwestern Scott County for several minutes. The funnel cloud was not associated with well-developed thunderstorms. Law enforcement personnel reported there was a brief touchdown in open fields, with no known damage.
A spotter reported a tornado just west of Highway 89 between Fairview and Birdseye. The tornado lasted about 10 minutes and remained over open country.

The tornado began northwest of Maddock and travelled along a path intermittently to near Flora and near Oberon.  A 40x60 foot metal shed was demolished.  About 2 miles northeast of Maddock, a grain bin was pulled from its foundation and thrown about 500 yards.  A hopper bin and concrete pad were also turned on end at this location.  Many large trees were flattened all along the path until the tornado weakened from Flora to near Oberon.

A grain elevator was heavily damaged and will likely be shut down for the rest of the year.  Many trees were uprooted and a camper was overturned.  1.5 miles of powerline was blown down with 24 poles snapped.
An auto repair shop had its roof torn off.  Many trees were uprooted, falling on signs, powerlines, homes, and garages.  Several grain bins were destroyed.
Numerous trees were blown down.
Storm spotters reported a (landspout) tornado near the intersection of County Road 225 and Farm-to-Market Road 214.  The tornado remained over open country.
The public reported and sent a digital picture of a (landspout) tornado to a local television station.  The tornado remained nearly stationary over open country.
Tornado touched down briefly in the southeast section of Burns.
Tornado touched down briefly 6 miles southeast of Burns near Wright's Point.
A brief landspout was reported along the outflow of a small thunderstorm.
Weak tornado (F0) damaged a couple of mobile homes and produced minor damage at a townhouse complex near Fort Eustis.
A weak tornado touched down briefly knocking down a few trees.
Another brief landspout was reported along the outflow of thunderstorms that formed in an environment of very weak shear.
Law enforcement officials reported a (landspout) tornado just east of town.  The tornado remained nearly stationary over open country.
A brief touchdown was reported.

A Small Tornado occurred in northwest Clearfield County. The path length of the tornado was approximately 3.5 miles long, and about 20 to 30 yards wide. The tornado began about 2 miles southeast of Luthersburg and continued northeast to about one half mile north of Anderson Station in Bloom Township. Intermittent touchdowns were reported along this path.
A tornado blew down power lines and poles, caused tree damage, flattened corn, and destroyed two machine sheds on a farm. Equipment inside the machine sheds was damaged.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.
A tornado damaged several small farm buildings, and peeled the middle part of the roof off a large hog confinement building.

A tornado completely destroyed at least ten houses and heavily damaged several others. The tornado heavily damaged the town school, including taking most of the roof off the school. The only church in town and a telephone company building were also heavily damaged. Power lines, poles, and trees were blown down, and electricity and water service were knocked out. Three empty box cars on the southeast side of Jackson were toppled. Three injuries included a woman with a broken leg and cuts rescued from the rubble of a house, and two children with minor injuries.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.

A tornado touched down northwest of Onawa overturning a center pivot irrigation system according to a law enforcement official.  The tornado was also captured on film from someone staying at the Lewis and Clark State Park.  All of the pictures taken showed that the condensation portion of the tornado was very narrow.  The path of the tornado crossed I-29 before lifting around 2 miles north northwest of Onawa.
A brief tornado caused no reported damage.

This tornado touched down east of Macy, Nebraska, on the Iowa side of the Missouri River.  This was the second tornado producing supercell to track across Monona county this night, touching down in open country with no apparent damage.  The tornado was first reported by law enforcement and was also caught on film by a tv meteorologist.  Initially the location was reported as Macy, Nebraska, but after further radar reviews, along with accounts from storm chasers at the scene, it was determined the tornado touched down west of Whiting, Iowa, or several miles east of Macy.
Several outbuilding destroyed and many crops flattened.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moisture streamed northeast into Iowa ahead of a cold front approaching from the north.  Dew point temperatures rose to +15 degrees C. at 850 mb by early evening.  At the same time, colder air was moving aloft.  This destabilized the atmosphere with thunderstorms erupting in northwest Iowa by late afternoon.  The small cluster of storms became severe and moved southeast into the DSM County Warning Area.  For the most part, the storms produced hail due to the low freezing level.  The freezing level was down to just over 12,000 feet at the time of the evening sounding at 0000 UTC.  Numerous reports of one  to two inch diameter hail were received from Crawford County southeast into Adams County.  A tornado touched down in Crawford County near Buck Grove.  The tornado tracked southeast a little over 6 miles, lifting just before crossing the Shelby County line southwest of Manilla.  The tornado downed power lines, destroyed several out buildings, and caused extensive crop damage along its path.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado briefly touched down 5.3 miles north of Mason City.  It ripped off a large top of a tree and carried it 100 feet.  One small tree was snapped.  All gutters on a house were lifted off, as well as a table being blown into a open garage door (facing south).  A door on the house was also blown open with the air moving through the attic in the house breaking out some windows.  A small shed nearby was intact. Fire officials about 1.5 miles south of the house saw swirling clouds over the house's location.  No injuries were reported.

A tornado formed along the leading edge of downburst winds just northwest of Dewitt. It moved southeast into town before lifting. It blew a chimney off of a church as well as some of its windows. Also, two homes sustained roof damage and a garage was blown down. Numerous large trees were ripped up and blown over. No injuries were reported.

A NWS site damage assessment determined a F0 tornado touched down on Broadridge Road, 1 1/2 miles off of Hwy 74W, six miles east of Fairmont.  It lifted a shed and carried it 15 yards.  Metal roofing was torn from a horse barn and a porch.  A chain link fence was also damaged.
A tornado briefly touched down in a field.  No damage or injuries were reported.
A brief touchdown was noted over an open field by an University of Illinois student and his wife. No damage was reported.

A supercell thunderstorm tracked east-southeast across southern Jefferson County. The storm produced a weak tornado that lasted for less than a minute. Evidence of the tornado consisted of damage to a corn field, strong rotation depicted on doppler radar, and an eyewitness account. Peak winds in the tornado were estimated at 70 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold air funnels were reported by the public and law enforcement officials, with a brief touchdown occurring near Osseo.  There were no reports of injuries or damage.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout moved onshore from Harbor Beach harbor. Once the waterspout made landfall, it become classified as a tornado. The tornado moved over the pier and went up a short hill near Water Street, then it dissipated. An elderly couple at an art fair attempted to hold onto belongings and were thrown to the ground with their belongings strewn on top of them. The elderly woman disslocated a shoulder and broke an arm, requireing an overnight hospital stay. One tree was also knocked over and fell onto a van.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system moved across the southern Great Lakes region. The cold air aloft with this low created enough instability to trigger scattered thunderstorms, most of which produced hail. A shower over the relatively warm waters of Lake Huron produced a waterspout which moved onshore as a tornado.

EVENT_NARRATIVE:
An F1 tornado touched down just southwest of the town of Duhring.  The tornado continued moving along a sporadic path to the northeast, exiting Forest County approximately 2 miles northeast of Duhring.

As the tornado passed near Duhring it reached its maximum path width of nearly 300 yards.  Winds estimated at 90 MPH downed around 250 trees.  Several of these trees fell on cabins, homes and vehicles.

A NWS storm survey team confirmed an F1 tornado touched down in Elk County.  The tornado first touched down in Forest County, then crossed into Elk County.   Damage was sporadic, with the initial touchdown in Elk county near the town of Highland. Sporadic damage between the towns of Highland and Nassen included 25 trees which were knocked down, and several more tree tops that were snapped off.  The path length of the tornado in Elk county was about 5 miles (the entire tornado path length including Forest and Elk counties was 10 miles). The width was 100 yards. Nickle size hail was also reported between Highland and Nassen. No injuries or fatalities occurred.

A tornado touched down in Hialeah and moved south southwest before lifting in the west Doral area.  The funnel was visible up to 10 miles away and was photographed by numerous people and the media.  No damage was observed along its path.  Another small funnel cloud also formed from the parent thunderstorm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A narrow and long, rope-like tornado was observed in Flaming Gorge National Recreation Area by at least 25 people.  The tornado was also photographed and videotaped. An eyewitness at the Red Canyon Visitors Center said the funnel cloud initially developed nearly overhead of the visitors center and moved south, touching down about a mile south of the visitors center near USFS Road 095.  The tornado traveled south along a path adjacent to USFS Road 095, crossed over the intersection of USFS Road 095 and state highway 44, and continued south up higher terrain.  The tornado than made an abrupt turn towards the east and followed highway 44 where it lifted up within a half mile of the Skull Creek Campground.  The tornado picked up brush, branches, and tree limbs along its path through the forested land.  Some of the debris was deposited on the roads.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small tornado briefly touched down in the Sugarhouse area of Salt Lake City. Other reports of the storm indicated a funnel cloud and strong thunderstorm winds. No damage or injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: There were several reports of a funnel cloud from law enforcement officials and spotters. The sightings were from the north side of Plainfield at the Will-Kendall County line near 111th and Route 30, east northeast to near 75th and Route 53 on the east side of Naperville. According to police, the funnel touched down briefly near Route 59 and 95th Street but there was no damage reported.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado touched down  in Merrillville just east of  the intersection of Merrillville Road and 84th Street. There was spotty minor structural damage in an industrial park with some small trees broken or pushed over, damage to signs and a few broken windows.  Many structures and trees in the path had no damage. Just west of I-65, parts of the roof and glass walls of a commercial building were damaged. East of I-65, just south of Route 30, there was more damage to signs. A semi was overturned. Two people were injured by broken glass at a restaurant in Hobart. Part of the roof and a section of a wall was blown out at a Kohl's department store. The tornado crossed Route 30 and caused minor structural damage, mostly to signs and glass, at a strip mall. Behind the shops, corn was flattened and trees were damaged.  The tornado then moved into the Green Acres subdivision near Colorado Street and 78th Street. A garage collapsed and many large tree limbs were blown down through the neighborhood. The tornado then weakened. Only minor damage to a few tree limbs occurred around the 7600 block of Clay Street and just south and east of the intersection of Grand and 73rd. The average path width was 50 yards.

A weak tornado spun up in north-central Kenosha County, about 3.5 miles northeast of Paris.  It pushed over an old shed, a TV antenna, and uprooted several trees on a property located on the south side of County Hwy KR. Based on damage, wind speeds were probably in the 70 to 78 knot range (80 to 90 mh).  This tornado exited Kenosha County about 3.7 miles northeast of Paris, or .8 miles east of the intersection of KR and D, and entered Racine County about 2.8 miles east-southeast of Union Grove.  It proceeded northeast toward the intersection of Interstate 94 and Highway 11, and eventually dissipated 1.8 miles northwest of Sturtevant.  Synoptically, a 500 mb circulation center moved northeast through southeast Wisconsin at the time of the tornado.  Scattered thunderstorms associated with the low moved northeast at about 30 mph.  Maximum air temperatures during the afternoon were in the lower 80s with surface dewpoints in the mid to upper 60s.

Thia weak tornado spun up in north-central Kenosha County, about 3.5 miles northeast of Paris.  It exited Kenosha County about 3.7 miles northeast of Paris, or .8 miles east of the intersection of KR and D, and entered Racine County about 2.8 miles east-southeast of Union Grove.  It proceeded northeast toward the intersection of Interstate 94 and Highway 11, and eventually dissipated 1.8 miles northwest of Sturtevant. Luckily, the tornado circulation wasn't at ground level the entire time, and traveled part of the time over some swamp land, otherwise there would have been more damage.  In Racine County, the tornado intensified to the top of the F1 rating (winds about 87 to 96 knots, or 100 to 110 mph), and demolished a hay shed, damaged a pole barn (horse trailer inside was pushed through a closed door), flattened some fence, uprooted or snapped many trees, damaged a road sign, damaged a Sheriff Department speed trailer at the I-94/Hwy 11 intersection, and flattened some corn crop.  A couple of power line poles were also damaged.  Eyewitness reports indicated that the tornado briefly consisted of multiple vortices, and sounded like a jet engine.  Average path length was about 25 yards.  Synoptically, a 500 mb circulation center moved northeast through southeast Wisconsin at the time of the tornado.  Scattered thunderstorms associated with the low moved northeast at about 30 mph.  Maximum air temperatures during the afternoon were in the lower 80s with surface dewpoints in the mid to upper 60s.
A small weak tornado touched down briefly on the north side of Wheeler. A few tree limbs were blown down and corn was flattened.
An F0 tornado touched down in a field approximately 3 miles southwest of the city of La Porte near the intersection of County Roads 400 South and 500 West. The only damage was to corn and beans.
A tornado was seen by an off duty NWS employee three miles south of Holbrook near the intersection of Routes 377 and 77.  The tornado was on the ground for 5 minutes.
A tornado was photographed by workers in an open field.  No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A tornado briefly touched down one mile southeast of Iberia and moved northeast for about one half mile. Damage was confined to trees and a shed.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm spotters reported a (landspout) tornado near the intersection of 82nd Street and Upland Avenue in the extreme southwestern city limits of Lubbock.  The tornado remained nearly stationary over an open field.
Deputies reported a brief  landspout tornado over open rangeland near Yeso.
Fire Department reported a tornado near FM 2351 and County Road 129.  Damage included a few metal roofs torn off buildings and trees down.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of upper level disturbances produced heavy rain and some severe weather across the southern portions of southeast Texas.  Rainfall rates of one inch per hour for up to 6 hours at a time were recorded in Jackson, Matagorda, and Wharton counties.  This led to widespread street flooding with some roads being washed out.  Heavy rainfall in Galveston, Brazoria, Fort Bend, and southeastern Harris counties also led to street flooding, as well as water in some homes.  The storms also produced three tornadoes causing minor damage and no injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Newspaper reported tornado touched down 2.5 miles southeast of Wild Peach Village.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tornado near Highway 65 between Monroe City and Winnie.  Law  enforcement reported no damage or injuries.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small tornado touched down in a wooded area just southwest of exit 165 on Interestate 20.  The tornado moved northeast moving across three structures on the south side of the Interstate, two of the structures suffered extensive damage.  The tornado moved across CR 207 where several trees were downed and a small portion of the roof of an unoccupied building was damaged.  It crossed two mobile home parks, downing trees, ripping pieces of siding from several mobile homes, and pushing one off it's foundation.  It crossed US 78 where another mobile home had some siding ripped away from it.  It moved through an open area that was inaccessible and then damaged several trees on the north side of the town of Lincoln.  No additional damage was found beyond that point.  The weak tornado came out of a bowing echo that also caused some damage mainly to trees in Calhoun County.  Beginning: 33 35.333N 86 10.056W  Ending:  33 37.564N 86 07.641W
